Since the circles with centers $Q$, $R$ and $S$ are tangent to $BC$, then $D$, $E$ and $F$ are the points of tangency of these circles to $BC$. Thus, $QD=SF=1$ and $RE=r$.

Join $QR$, $RS$, $PS$, $PQ$, and $PR$. Since we are connecting centers of tangent circles, $PQ=PS=2$ and $QR=RS=PR=1+r$.

Join $QS$. By symmetry, $PRE$ is a straight line (that is, $PE$ passes through $R$). Since $QS$ is parallel to $BC$, $QS$ is perpendicular to $PR$, meeting at $Y$.

Since $QD=1$, $YE=1$.  Since $RE=r$, $YR=1-r$. Since $QR=1+r$, $YR=1-r$ and $\triangle QYR$ is right-angled at $Y$, then by the Pythagorean Theorem,
\begin{align*}
QY^2 &= QR^2 - YR^2\\
&= (1+r)^2 - (1-r)^2 \\
&= (1+2r+r^2)-(1-2r+r^2) \\
&= 4r.
\end{align*}Since $PR=1+r$ and $YR=1-r$, then $PY = PR-YR=2r$. Since $\triangle PYQ$ is right-angled at $Y$,
\begin{align*}
PY^2 + YQ^2 & = PQ^2 \\
(2r)^2 + 4r & = 2^2 \\
4r^2 + 4r & =4 \\
r^2 + r - 1 & = 0.
\end{align*}By the quadratic formula, $r = \dfrac{-1\pm \sqrt{1^2-4(1)(-1)}}{2} = \dfrac{-1\pm\sqrt{5}}{2}$.
Since $r>0$, then $r = \dfrac{-1+\sqrt{5}}{2}$ (which is the reciprocal of the famous ``golden ratio"). Thus, $a+b+c=-1+5+2=\boxed{6}$.

