Find $a+b+c$, given that $x+y\neq -1$ and  \begin{align*}
ax+by+c&=x+7,\\
a+bx+cy&=2x+6y,\\
ay+b+cx&=4x+y.
\end{align*}

chain_of_thought:
Since these equations look symmetric, at least on the left-hand side, we add all three together.  This gives us  \begin{align*}
&a(x+1+y)+b(y+x+1)+c(1+y+x)\\
&\qquad\qquad=x+7+2x+6y+4x+y.
\end{align*} We then factor out $(1+x+y)$ on the left and simplify the right side to get \begin{align*}
(1+x+y)(a+b+c)&=7x+7y+7, \text{ so}\\
(1+x+y)(a+b+c)&=7(1+x+y).
\end{align*}

Since $x+y\neq -1$, we know $x+y+1\neq 0$, so we can divide both sides by that term and find that $a+b+c=\boxed{7}$.

Instead of expanding the entire product, we can look only at terms that will multiply to give $x^3$.  We know that $$x^3=x^3\cdot 1=x^2\cdot x=x\cdot x^2=1\cdot x^3.$$Knowing this, the $x^3$ term in the expansion will be the sum of these four terms: $$(6x^3)(4)+(4x^2)(3x)+(-7x)(3x^2)+(-5)(6x^3).$$We simplify to find: \begin{align*}
&(6x^3)(4)+(4x^2)(3x)+(-7x)(3x^2)+(-5)(6x^3)\\
&\qquad=24x^3+12x^3-21x^3-30x^3\\
&\qquad=\boxed{-15}x^3
\end{align*}

We just plug into our function definitions given in the problem:

\begin{align*}
f(g(7)) + g(f(3)) &= f(7 + 7) + g(3^2 - 1) \\
&= f(14) + g(8) = (14^2 - 1) + (8 + 7) \\
&= 195 + 15 = \boxed{210}
\end{align*}

